Polar bears are not the first species (nor will they likely be the last) for which we have sought the protections of the Endangered Species Act because of global warming.
Polar bears are not the only species threatened by global warming.
In December, Interior Secretary Dirk Kempthorne proposed listing polar bears as a threatened species.
With the loss of sea ice, the worldwide population of polar bears--estimated at about 20,000 to 25,000--has steadily declined.
Faced with incontrovertible evidence that polar bears are imperiled, Interior Secretary Dirk Kempthorne agreed recently to designate polar bears as threatened under the Endangered Species Act.
